# Architecture

- Keep exactly three production projects unless a concrete deployment boundary appears: App, Core, Infrastructure.
- Core must not reference App or Infrastructure.
- App is the only composition root; keep `Program.cs` and DI registration thin.
- Add a package, service, project, interface, base class, or pattern only for a concrete requirement; record non-obvious decisions in README/ADR.
- Do not introduce MediatR, AutoMapper, CQRS, event sourcing, a generic repository, Redis, RabbitMQ, Kafka, or an in-memory work frontier.
- Prefer concrete internal classes. Create interfaces only at external boundaries or where the assignment explicitly requires polymorphic extension.
- Never place business/crawl policy in controllers, `Program.cs`, SQL mapping code, or content parser adapters.

# Dependency direction

- `BrightCrawler.Core` owns ports and workflow semantics.
- `BrightCrawler.Infrastructure` implements Core ports.
- Infrastructure-specific types (`Npgsql*`, `HttpClient`, parser-library models, filesystem paths) must not leak into Core contracts.
- Do not create generic `Common`, `Shared`, `Helpers`, or `Services` dumping-ground folders.
